-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Sun Resorts of Mauritius
-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 2012-02-29T16:10:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-29/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-sun-resorts-of-mauritius.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  fell for a
seventh day, retreating 0.6 percent to 1,773.32 by the end of
trading, the lowest since October 2010.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  advanced for the seventh straight
day to 1.6 percent to 58.84 in Nairobi, the longest rally since
January 2011. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  fell
for a third day, sliding 0.1 percent to 20,123.51 as of 2:30
p.m. in Lagos, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  rose for a second day, gaining 0.4
percent to 924.54 in Windhoek.  The following shares were active in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC)  , the Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African countries, gained for a fourth day,
climbing 0.4 percent to 11.6 shillings, the highest since Aug.
4, after the Nairobi-based company said full-year profit surged
70 percent as sales more than doubled after the market close
yesterday.  Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the East African
nation’s biggest lender by assets, extended gains for a fourth
day, increasing 1.2 percent to 20.5 shillings, the highest since
Aug. 18, on speculation full-year earnings will increase.  “KCB Bank is expected to continue trading actively with
increased demand being observed on the stock” ahead of its 2011
results which will probably be released March 1, Nairobi-based
Kestrel Capital East Africa Ltd. said in an e-mailed note today.  Sun Resorts Ltd. (SUN)  (SUN MP), Mauritius’s second-largest
resort group, fell for a second day, slumping 4.9 to 39 rupees,
the lowest since April 2009 as investors anticipate lower full-
year earnings. The company’s loss in the third quarter through
September widened to 172.5 million rupees from 133 million
rupees a year earlier, Sun Resorts reported Nov. 15.  To contact the reporter on this story:
